				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t}\gamma $$\end{document} signal and the dominating background, which is tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t}$$\end{document} production with a hadronic-fake or electron-fake photon. In the dilepton channel, this is not the case since Zγ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
