The systematic uncertainties of the unfolded distributions are decomposed into the signal modelling uncertainty, experimental uncertainty, and background modelling uncertainty in both channels. In the single-lepton (dilepton) channel, the background modelling uncertainty is split into tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t}$$\end{document} (Zγ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Z\gamma $$\end{document}) and the others. These decomposed uncertainties are illustrated in Figs. 11 and 12 for the single-lepton and dilepton channels, respectively. For the single-lepton channel, the systematic uncertainty is dominated by the tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t}$$\end{document} modelling, which is used to model the shapes of the hadronic-fake and electron-fake backgrounds. For the dilepton channel, the systematic uncertainty is dominated by the Zγ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Z\gamma $$\end{document} modelling, mostly from the comparison between Sherpa and MG5_aMC+Pythia 8 generators. Because the unfolding is performed with the distributions before the fit, the background modelling uncertainties are not constrained as in the case of fiducial cross-section measurement where a fit to ELD distribution is performed, and thus they have a much larger impact on the result.

